
[p|Markup language]
[p|From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia[a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markup_language#mw-head)|Jump to navigation][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markup_language#p-search)|Jump to search]For other uses, see[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markup_\(disambiguation\))|Markup (disambiguation)].[a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:RecipeBook_XML_Example.png)|[img url(https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/e/ee/RecipeBook_XML_Example.png/220px-RecipeBook_XML_Example.png)]][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:RecipeBook_XML_Example.png)]Example of RecipeBook, a simple language based on XML for creating recipes. The markup can be converted to[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML)|HTML],[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portable_Document_Format)|PDF][_]and[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_Text_Format)|Rich Text Format]using a[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language)|programming language][_]or[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extensible_Stylesheet_Language)|XSL].]
[p|In computer text processing, a[_][b|markup language][_]is a system for[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Annotation)|annotating][_]a[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Document)|document][_]in a way that is[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syntax_\(logic\))|syntactically distinguishable][_]from the text.[a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markup_language#cite_note-1)|\[1\]][_]The idea and terminology evolved from the "marking up" of paper manuscripts, i.e., the revision instructions by editors, traditionally written with a[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_pencil_\(editing\))|blue pencil][_]on authors'[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manuscript)|manuscripts].\[[i|[a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed)|citation needed]]\][_]In[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_media)|digital media], this "blue pencil instruction text" was replaced by[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML_element)|tags], that is, instructions are expressed directly by tags or "instruction text encapsulated by tags." However the whole idea of a mark up language is to avoid the formatting work for the text, as the tags in the mark up language serve the purpose to format the appropriate text (like a header or beginning of a next para...etc.). Every tag used in a Markup language has a property to format the text we write.]
[p|Examples include typesetting instructions such as those found in[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troff)|troff],[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TeX)|TeX][_]and[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LaTeX)|LaTeX], or structural markers such as[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extensible_Markup_Language)|XML][_]tags. Markup instructs the software that displays the text to carry out appropriate actions, but is omitted from the version of the text that users see.]
[p|Some markup languages, such as the widely used[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML)|HTML], have pre-defined[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Presentation_semantics)|presentation semantics]meaning that their specification prescribes how to present the[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Structured_data)|structured data]. Others, such as XML, do not have them and are general purpose.]
[p|[a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypertext)|HyperText][_]Markup Language (HTML), one of the document formats of the[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Wide_Web)|World Wide Web], is an instance of[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_Generalized_Markup_Language)|Standard Generalized Markup Language][_]or SGML, and follows many of the markup conventions used in the publishing industry in the communication of printed work between authors, editors, and printers.\[[i|[a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed)|citation needed]]\]]
